english:
  title: A Farewell Sequence for the Emissary Yi Gong, Returning to the Capital
  author: Byeon Gyeyangn
  language: eng
  text: Though Joseon lies beyond the seas, it has been blessed to receive the teachings rooted in the virtue of Jizi. Our people know loyalty and filial piety; our customs honor propriety and righteousness. We revere the Central Kingdom and serve as dutiful subjects, generation after generation without wavering. How much more so when our sovereign, by nature loyal and reverent, serves the great court with utmost sincerity. Though we remit tribute according to the seasons, we constantly fear our offerings fall short of what is due. Yet the generous care bestowed upon us spurs us to greater diligence in our duties. The Son of Heaven, perceiving our deepest intentions, has shown ever-deepening favor. In the spring of the eighteenth year of Yongle, the Son of Heaven, mindful of how our late sovereign reverently served the great realm, bestowed upon him the noble posthumous title of Gongjing, and further decreed sacrificial rites and special words of consolation. To convey these commands and ceremonies, he chose the Prefect of Rites, Lord Zhao, and the Emissary Yi Gong, whom he dispatched from the imperial court to proclaim the celestial grace. When the embassy reached our borders, our king sent officials to receive them. On the eighth day of the fourth month, the mission arrived at the outskirts of our capital. The king, with all his ministers, came forth to the Tower of Admiration for the Chinese to greet the emissary, conducting him to the lodge where, with the utmost reverence, he received the imperial mandate. Joy filled the hearts of ruler and subjects alike, and the people of the capital, from elders to youth, celebrated with delight—such was their gratitude for the imperial grace and respect for the emissary's mission. When the embassy completed its duties and prepared to return, the gentlemen of our court held such deep admiration for Lord Yi that they lamented the hastiness of his departure and could not bear to see him go. Thus they composed verses to send him on his way and entrusted me with writing this preface. I reflect that the Ministry of Rites governs the ritual and music of an entire age, while the Emissary receives the distinguished guests of all realms. How weighty is this responsibility—how could it be abandoned from the presence of the Son of Heaven even for a day? Now that they have come to us, I am moved all the more by the benevolence with which the Holy Son of Heaven honors our small realm. Moreover, Lord Yi possesses an upright heart and keen intellect; his speech and bearing serve as a model for all. Surely he does not merely execute his duties as an emissary to distant lands, but shall henceforth, morning and night, illuminate and assist the sacred virtue of the sovereign. Upon his return to stand before the imperial throne, let him recount our king's sincere reverence for Heaven and devoted service to the greater realm. Then shall mutual trust flourish between sovereign and subject, and the transformative influence of the great court extend eternally to the east. What greater fortune could there be? Let the emissary hold this intention close to heart.
  footnotes:
    - 'Jizi (箕子): A legendary sage-king of ancient China who is credited with teaching virtues to Korea, making him an important symbolic figure in Korean-Chinese cultural relations.'
    - 'Yongle (永樂): The reign period of the Ming emperor Yongle (1402-1424), establishing the historical context of this diplomatic exchange.'
    - 'Tower of Admiration for the Chinese (慕華樓): A symbolic structure representing Korea''s respect for Chinese civilization and proper place for receiving imperial envoys.'
    - The 'Eastern influence' (東漸之化) refers to the spreading of Ming Chinese civilization and virtue toward the east, a concept central to the tributary system.
